Step-by-step reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanism: Participants’ proposals as proposers are influenced by fairness perceptions. They compare their own token count with that of their opponent, which serves as a cue for what constitutes a “fair” division.
2. Interaction of mechanisms: A fairness ratio is computed by taking the opponent’s tokens relative to the total tokens. A participant then adjusts a baseline (often an equal 50% split) by the deviation of this ratio from fairness (0.5). When the opponent has more tokens, the fairness ratio is above 0.5 leading to a higher proposed percentage for the opponent; when the participant has more, it is below 0.5 and the proposed percentage is lowered.
3. Mathematical Form: A linear function is used, in which the predicted proposed percentage for the opponent is equal to a baseline (beta0) plus a sensitivity (beta1) times the deviation of the observed fairness ratio from ideal fairness.
4. Parameters: Two learnable parameters are employed:
 • beta0 (baseline or intercept parameter) representing the proposed percentage when tokens are equally distributed.  
 • beta1 (sensitivity parameter) representing how strongly the fairness deviation affects the proposal.
 Both parameters will have generous finite bounds.
5. Mapping to observable behavior: The model predicts the value of "proposed_perc" using the token counts provided in each trial through the fairness ratio: (token_opp/(token_self+token_opp)). This links the experimental data directly to the output behavior.

